note.body: I think we should also check the human player isn't in a dead end.
For human players I think we would make sure their new location and direction has a good run of spaces in front.

Actually using the random teleporter is probably always a bad idea for a human, since the risk of winding up in a bad location and immediately dying is very high, and that outweighs any potential benefit. But I suppose it could be interesting for the AI, which has superhuman reflexes.

> Does the random teleporter always appear in the same location or is that random too?

Always the same location.

> Does the random teleporter stay in a fix location, move or disappear/reappear?

Always the same location.

And there was only one in the entire game. It was removed [here](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-nibbles/-/commit/d63375289d855d0cfd34be86bec59c6a604434a6).

> How does the AI behave with a random teleporter? Does it for example know that it is in a race for an apple that its going to loose to another worm unless it takes the chance and uses the random teleporter?

I think you get to answer this one. :D The original AI apparently didn't even know about it.

Michael, I think a random teleporter sounds fun but I need more details about how it worked?
1) Does the random teleporter always appear in the same location or is that random too?
2) Does the random teleporter stay in a fix location, move or disappear/reappear?
3) How does the AI behave with a random teleporter? Does it for example know that it is in a race for an apple that its going to loose to another worm unless it takes the chance and uses the random teleporter?
